On Sat, 2004-06-19 at 07:14, David Goodwin wrote:
&gt; Karl,
&gt; 
&gt; Yes, the flow controllers have changed in 1.5.4, and are now simpler.   
&gt; The use of a PID controller seemed to be overkill, and has now been  
&gt; removed (but can be restored if desired).  If you are writing your code  
&gt; in C++, take a look at Cantera/src/zeroD/flowControllers.h. It defines  
&gt; the existing flow controllers, which are MassFlowController, Valve, and  
&gt; a new one PressureController.  A PressureController is designed to go  
&gt; on an outlet of a reactor, and is slaved to another flow controller on  
&gt; an inlet.  Its mass flow rate is equal to the inlet flow controller&#39;s  
&gt; mass flow rate, plus a term linear in the pressure difference.  This  
&gt; allows easily maintaining a constant pressure in a reactor with  
&gt; time-varying input mass flow rate.
&gt; 
&gt; Use it as shown here:
&gt; 
&gt; FlowDevice *mfc, *pc;
&gt; mfc = new MassFlowController();
&gt; pc = new PressureController();
&gt; pc-&gt;setMaster(mfc):
&gt; 
&gt; Set the coefficient of the linear term the same way you would for a  
&gt; valve (method setParameters). If your code is Python or Matlab, the  
&gt; syntax is simpler.  This will all be covered in the document I am  
&gt; finishing up now that should be done in a few days.
&gt; 
&gt; Dave
